In February 1761, a Boston lawyer named James Otis stood before the Massachusetts Superior Court and argued for five hours against the Writs of Assistance, British instruments authorizing customs officials to search any premises, at any time, without specific cause or judicial oversight.

The writs were legal under British law. Otis argued they were tyrannical anyway.

He called them "the worst instrument of arbitrary power, the most destructive of English liberty and the fundamental principles of law, that ever was found in an English law book." He argued that legality does not confer legitimacy, that a law violating natural rights is void regardless of what Parliament enacted. The power to search everyone, he warned, is the power to control everyone. General warrants place "the liberty of every man in the hands of every petty officer."

John Adams, then a young lawyer watching from the gallery, later wrote: "Then and there the child Independence was born."

A statute enacted to expand voting access was never meant to justify mass federal collection of personal data on every registered voter in a state.

The founders did not rebel against illegal acts. The Stamp Act was legal. The Quartering Act was legal. The Writs of Assistance were legal under British law.
